1. Purpose and scope
Collection of compact, efficient bitwise algorithms and idioms for integer manipulation and low-level operations useful in performance-critical code.

2. Common bit-twiddling primitives (implementation-ready)
- Isolate lowest set bit (LSB): lsb = x & -x  (two's complement property)
- Clear lowest set bit: x & (x - 1)
- Test for power of two (and non-zero): (x & (x - 1)) == 0 && x != 0
- Round up to next power of two (32-bit unsigned):
  v = v - 1
  v = v | (v >> 1)
  v = v | (v >> 2)
  v = v | (v >> 4)
  v = v | (v >> 8)
  v = v | (v >> 16)
  v = v + 1
- Count trailing zeros (ctz) (portable fallback using binary search or loop):
  if x == 0 return width; count = 0; while ((x & 1) == 0) { x >>= 1; count++; }
- Integer log2 (floor): use position of highest set bit via shifts or builtins (31 - clz(x) for 32-bit).
- Parity (odd number of 1s): parity = x ^ (x >> 1); x ^= x >> 2; x = (x & 0x11111111) * 0x11111111 >> 28 & 1 (or use popcount(x) & 1).

3. SWAR/popcount patterns (compact reference)
- 32-bit popcount SWAR:
  x -= (x >> 1) & 0x55555555
  x = (x & 0x33333333) + ((x >> 2) & 0x33333333)
  x = (x + (x >> 4)) & 0x0F0F0F0F
  x += x >> 8
  x += x >> 16
  return x & 0x3F
- Multiply-shift byte-sum technique for some platforms; use when overflow and endianness accounted for.

4. Utility transformations
- Reverse bits: iterative table or divide-and-conquer swaps using masks and shifts (swap halves, quarters, etc.)
- Pack/unpack bitfields: mask & shift sequences; use SHIFT then OR.

5. Troubleshooting and portability notes
- Beware signed right shift on negative values; use unsigned shifts when logical shift is required.
- Endianness matters when reading multibyte words from byte arrays; prefer word reads only when alignment and endianness are controlled.
- For languages without native unsigned types, mask results (e.g., >>> 0 in JS) to avoid sign extension.

